Evaluation of the Ebola Data and Statistics¶

by Uchanma Adeola Igbokwe¶

Introduction¶

The source of this dataset is the World Health Organization (WHO). Contributions were made by HDX. It provides data for the total number of probable, confirmed and suspected Ebola cases and deaths in Guinea, Liberia, Sierra Leone, Nigeria, Senegal, Mali, Spain, the USA, the United Kingdom and Italy according to Ebola Data and Statistics. The date of the dataset is August 29, 2014 to March 23, 2016 and last updated on 10 November, 2019. The dataset contains approximately 17585 entries.

Ebola virus disease (EVD) is a deadly disease with occasional outbreaks that occur mostly on the African continent. EVD most commonly affects people and nonhuman primates (such as monkeys, gorillas, and chimpanzees). It is caused by an infection with a group of viruses within the genus Ebolavirus(Centre for Disease Control[CDC], 2021).

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 36 unique indicators in this dataset. The dataset is in the long format, meaning that variables/indicators are entered as rows. There are 10 countries with values for each indicator listed and on dates between 29th August 2014 to 29th December 2015. And other observations for 2016.

Analysis cannot be carried out on the dataset as it is, therefore, data cleaning needs to be done.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am interested in examining the 'Cumulative number of confirmed Ebola deaths', the 'Cumulative number of probable Ebola cases' and the Case fatality rate (CFR) of confirmed Ebola cases.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

My hypothesis is that as the number of deaths increases, the more confirmed cases of Ebola. To get this, I will examine how the column variables "Cumulative number of confirmed Ebola cases" relates to the variable "Cumulative number of confirmed Ebola deaths".

I would also like to see the distribution of confirmed Ebola deaths in the various countries.

I would also examine the trends in confirmed Ebola deaths as the date progressed. This would help me know whether confirmed deaths increased or decreased as the outbreak progressed. This might be an indication of how well the cases were being handled in each country.

How does the cumulative number of confirmed Ebola cases compare to the cumulative number of probable Ebola cases?

Examine how the case fatality rates compare in the countries for the period of outbreak.

#plotting histograms.
def myhist(ebola_df, xvar, bins):
    
    # A simple function created to avoid code repetition. It is to be used in plotting histograms of various movie properties within this notebook.
    #inputs : variables to be plotted
    #outputs: scatter plots of dependent variables against independent variable.
    
    #Plots
    plt.figure(figsize =(18, 7))
    sb.histplot(data= ebola_df, x=xvar, color = 'green', bins= bins);
    
    #Formats chart titles and labels
    #Tidy labels
    xvar = xvar.replace("_"," ") #replace _ with a space

    #Formats x-axis
    plt.xlabel(xvar.title(), fontsize=15)
    
    #Formats y-axis

#creating scatterplots function for bivariate and multipvariate exploration of variables.

def myScatterPlot(ebola_df, xVar, yVar):

    # A simple function created to avoid code repetition. It is to be used in plotting scatter plots within this notebook.
    #inputs : variables to be plotted
    #outputs: scatter plots of dependent variables against independent variable.

    # Plots
    ebola_df.plot(kind= 'scatter', x= xVar, y= yVar, figsize=[19,8], color = 'green');

    # After plotting, tidy up labels
    xVar= xVar.replace("_"," ") #replace _ with a space
    yVar= yVar.replace("_"," ") #replace _ with a space

    # Add title and format it
    plt.title(f'Relationship between {yVar} and {xVar}'.title(), fontsize =14, weight = "bold")

    # Add x label and format it
    plt.xlabel(xVar.title(), fontsize = 12, weight = "bold")


    # Add y label and format it
    plt.ylabel(yVar.title(), fontsize = 12, weight = "bold")

# Examining the relationship between relevant numeric values using a pairgrid.
# Selecting numeric variables
num_vars = ['total_confirmed_deaths', 'total_probable_cases', 'case_fatality_rate', 'total_confirmed_cases', 'total_suspected_cases', 'total_probable_deaths']

# Create plot

p.map_offdiag(plt.scatter);

From the pairgrid, total confirmed cases and total suspected cases seem to have a positive linear relationship with total confirmed deaths. This is expected for total confirmed cases because it is likely that as the number of confirmed cases increase, so will the likelihood of the number of deaths. The same cannot be said for total probable cases and total confirmed deaths, the relationship between them is not clear.

A correlation plot will be plotted to see the correlation coefficient of these variables. A scatterplot of confirmed deaths and confirmed cases will be created to get a clearer picture of their relationship.

In [47]:

plt.figure(figsize = [11, 7])

Unsurprisingly, the correlation coefficient of the confirmed cases and confirmed deaths is 0.97, this is a very stong positive relationship. Therefore, in most cases, as the number of confirmed cases increases, so does the number of deaths.

The correlation between confirmed deaths and probable cases is also positive since r is 0.65.

For total probable cases and total confirmed cases, there is a weak positive relationship(r= 0.38). This is completely unexpected because probable cases are usually those are most expected to become confirmed cases, even more liekly than suspected cases.

The effect of the number of confirmed cases on the number of deaths is confirmed even more in this section when both variables are plotted within the date context. There are no similarities in the pattern of number of confirmed deaths, number of probable cases and number of confirmed cases. Geographical similarities like in the African countries did not seem to make patterns in confirmed cases or probable cases similar.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was surprising to notice that despite the relative closeness of the affected African Countries, there was no apparent similar pattern in the deaths and cases recorded. Of no surprise is the trend of the number of cases in the European countries.

Conclusions¶

With the aid of various visualization methods, we examined the Ebola data and statistics recorded for the 2014 outbreak and concluded that the severity of the outbreak was greatest in Guinea, Sierra Leone and Nigeria, respectively putting into consideration their case fatality rate for the duration of the outbreak. It was also great to identify four countries that had the least number of confirmed cases and recorded no deaths. In no particular order, these countries are the United Kindgom, Italy, Spain and Senegal. It might be worthy to commend Liberia because though it had the second largest number of confirmed cases, when compared with the confirmed deaths, the treatment and management of patients was successful.

One of the goals of this investigation was to identify whether there was a relationship between confirmed deaths and confirmed cases. This was noted to be positive, observing that as the number of confirmed cases increased, so did the number of deaths. Contrary to what was initially thought, there was a weak positive relationship between the number of probable cases and the number of confirmed cases.

The World Health Organization(WHO) stated that the average case fatality rate is 50%. Most countries had case fatality rates below this according to the dataset analyzed.
